Tom's point about change and growth is well taken, and in certain areas this applies, however, the use of these words would change the meaning of my questions and, thus, I need to stick with that word. A couple examples so that I don't seem to be vague, and we can bounce these around.<br><br>
Barry's involvement with the civil rights movement of the 60's and Barry's attitude about the Vietnamese in the 90's. Many of us had agree that there were ingredients of racism in his writings. How did this come about?<br><br>
Barry's radicalism and anti-government of the sixties versus his rendition of Uncle Sam, Mom, and Apple Pie (this is not a put down!)when he went to the air show and his views of flag desecration that he voiced on another thread.<br><br>
These are two signs of a much bigger picture, a much bigger change than appears in part I. <br><br>
Change, yes, but growth? The word growth and the description of you and your father implies a movement upward or foward. In these two instances, the first was a movement backwards and the second could be argued either way.<br><br>
I think that all agree that the time Barry had spent on the site we have seen growth in each of us in some ways and radical growth (my interpretation) in him. Somewhere along the line between two years after doing his hospital service to when he first came on site, there were changes that occured that illustrate certain inconsistencies.
